ellow Quakers.In the first biography of Mott in a generation, historian Carol Faulkner reveals the motivations of this radical egalitarian from Nantucket. Mott's deep faith and ties to the Society of Friends do not fully explain her activism—her roots in post-Revolutionary New England also shaped her views on slavery, patriarchy, and the church, as well as her expansive interests in peace, temperance, prison reform, religious freedom, and Native American rights. While Mott was known as the "moving spirit" of the first women's rights convention at Seneca Falls, her commitment to women's rights never trumped her support for abolition or racial equality. She envisioned women's rights not as a new and separate movement but rather as an extension of the universal principles of liberty and equality. Mott was among the first white Americans to call for an immediate end to slavery. Her long-term collaboration with white and black women in the Philadelphia Female Anti-Slavery Society was remarkable by any standards. Lucretia Mott's Heresy reintroduces readers to an amazing woman whose work and ideas inspired the transformation of American society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryx19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aFeministszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aQuaker womenzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen abolitionistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen social reformerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistoryx19th century. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAfrican Studies.  aAfrican-American Studies.  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGender Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part o